@node Over "Overview"

Report+ is a freeware ReAction-based utility with nine functions:

@{" 1." link 1} It is an enhanced, reverse-engineered, 100% byte-compatible
     replacement for the official Commodore bug reporting tool (V40.2),
     optionally sending emails automatically.
@{" 2." link 2} It can generate/edit Aminet-style readmes.
@{" 3." link 3} It can load/save/edit A3000/A4000-type battery-backed memory.
@{" 4." link 4} It can access the official manufacturer and product ID registries.
@{" 5." link 5} It can view IFF/RIFF files and their component chunks.
@{" 6." link 6} It can perform batch processing on icons.
@{" 7." link 7} It can convert between various ASCII formats.
@{" 8." link 8} It can show directory byte usage for any path, optionally also fixing
     protection bits and/or deleting files.
@{" 9." link 9} It can take a snapshot of a path and later compare the
     path against this, showing added, missing and changed files.
@endnode

@node Requ "System Requirements"

@{b}Hardware@{ub}    Required       MC68020+
                           about 1Mb free RAM
            Recommended    Modem
                           Battery-backed clock
                           A3000/A4000-style battery-backed memory
                           additional RAM
                           1024*768 or higher Workbench
@{b}Firmware@{ub}    Required       Kickstart 3.1+
@{b}Software@{ub}    Required       AmigaOS 3.9 with Boing Bag 1 (at least)
            Recommended    boards.library (included)
                           openpci.library (included)
                           OpenURL.library (if OS < OS4.1.1)
                           TCP/IP stack

This program does not operate under the "AmigaOS 3.x" provided by Cloanto
in eg. the Amiga Forever 6.0 package, as it requires OS3.9+BB1 (or later)
versions of certain ReAction gadgets. The versions included in "AmigaOS
3.x" are obsolete and will not work. We suggest asking Cloanto for the
real OS3.9 which you have paid them for and which they have not supplied
to you, rather than a crippled version of OS3.5 which is basically what
their "AmigaOS 3.x" is.

If you have the Amiga Image Storage System (AISS) installed, you can
delete the images/aiss/ subdirectory.
  You may be interested in the full boards.library package; you can get
it from http://aminet.net/util/libs/BoardsLib.lha .

For MorphOS users:

You need the appropriate ClassAct/ReAction classes (eg. window.class,
speedbar.gadget, etc.) installed. You can get these classes at
http://amigan.1emu.net/releases/RA-MOS.lha . Those files are sourced from
AmigaOS 3.9+BB2, except that window.class V42.84 is provided instead of
V45.16. This is because MorphOS is incompatible with window.class 45.16:
opening it will cause a hang. Simply copy these ReAction classes into
SYS:Classes/ . Although they are compiled for 68020, they will work under
MorphOS.
@endnode

@node Usag "Usage"

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

                                 @{b}ReportPlus@{ub}

@{b}Format:    ReportPlus@{ub} [PUBSCREEN <pubscreen>]
           [[FUNCTION] <function> [RESET [TIMEOUT] [LUNS] [SYNC_XFER]
           [SLOW_SYNC] [TAG_QUEUES] [HOST_ID <host_id>]]
           [ICONTYPE=APPICON|DEVICE|DISK|DRAWER|KICKSTART|PROJECT|TOOL|
           TRASHCAN] [OPTIMIZE=ON|OFF] [PLANAR=ON|OFF]
           [SOURCE=AMIGA|IBM|MAC] [DEST=AMIGA|IBM|MAC]
           [[FILE] <file(s)...>]]

@{b}Template:@{ub}  PUBSCREEN/K,FUNCTION/N,RESET/S,TIMEOUT/S,LUNS/S,
           SYNC_XFER/S,SLOW_SYNC/S,TAG_QUEUES/S,HOST_ID/K/N,ICONTYPE/K,
           PLANAR/K,OPTIMIZE/K,FILE/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}   To run the Report+ utility.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    pubscreen=<pubscreen>:
           the name of a public screen to open on (otherwise the default
           public screen is used).

    -n:    don't display Report+ logo.

    function=1|2|3|4|5|6|7|8|9:
           the ordinal number of the function you wish to jump to. These
           correspond as follows:

            1  Bug report editor
            2  Aminet readme editor
            3  Battery-backed RAM editor
            4  Hardware ID database viewer
            5  IFF/RIFF viewer
            6  Icon processor
            7  ASCII converter
            8  Path size report
            9  Path differences report

    reset: this switch will cause the battery-backed RAM to be
           overwritten. Of course, <function> must be 9. What is written
           to it depends on the TIMEOUT, LUNS, SYNC_XFER, SLOW_SYNC,
           TAG_QUEUES, and HOST_ID arguments.

    timeout, luns, sync_xfer, slow_sync, tag_queues, host_id <host_id>:
           these modify the behaviour of the RESET switch. See @{"here" link 3}
           for more information.

    icontype=appicon|device|disk|drawer|kickstart|project|tool|trashcan,
    optimize=on|off, planar=on|off:
           these can be used to modify the behaviour of the icon
           processor. <function> must be 6. If you don't specify these,
           the behaviour is according to what is read from the
           ReportPlus.config file (or, if that does not exist, the factory
           defaults, which are ICONTYPE=DRAWER, OPTIMIZE=ON, PLANAR=OFF).

    source=amiga|ibm|mac, dest=amiga|ibm|mac:
           these can be used to modify the behaviour of the ASCII
           processor. <function> must be 7. If you don't specify these,
           the behaviour is according to what is read from the
           ReportPlus.config file (or, if that does not exist, the factory
           defaults, which are SOURCE=IBM, DEST=AMIGA).

    file=<files>:
           a list of files for the ASCII converter or icon processor to
           process, if <function> is 6 or 7, respectively, or...

    file=<file>:
           a file to be opened by the bug report editor, Aminet
           readme editor or IFF/RIFF viewer, if <function> is 1, 2 or
           5, respectively, or...

           or a path to be examined by the path sizes reporter or the
           path differences reporter, if <function> is 8 or 9,
           respectively.

           (Functions 3 and 4 do not accept CLI filenames).

@{b}Workbench Tool Types@{ub}

These are only usable if you recompile Report+ with SAS/C.

PUBSCREEN=<pubscreen>
FUNCTION=<function>

These are equivalent to the relevant CLI arguments.
@endnode

@node 1 "Bug Report Editor"

This function replicates the functionality of the official bug report
generator, with these improvements:

    * ReAction rather than console interface
    * loading/editing/saving of preexisting bug reports
    * emailing of bug reports
    * ability to handle reports for any arbitrary program

It is primarily intended for generating bug reports but can also be used
by developers to view such reports in a friendly manner.
  You can use Ctrl-Up and Ctrl-Down to scroll to the extremes of the
listview.
  If a TCP/IP stack is operative, you are able to email the bug report
by pressing the `Send Email' button. You can only do this after you have
filled out the `Summary', `SMTP Host' and `Sender Email' fields. If the
`SMTP Host' gadget is ghosted, no TCP/IP stack was detected on your
machine.
  S:Report.sender and S:Report.config are used for the sender and
configuration data, respectively, in the same format as used by Report.
  S:Report.ks and S:Report.wb are not used, as Report+ extracts version
data directly from the relevant KICKSTART and WORKBENCH environment
variables.
  The SMTPHOST global environment variable is read and written for the
desired SMTP host.
  Note that the destination email address and SMTP host name are not saved
as part of the bug report, to maintain compatibility with the official
Report format.
  The 'Subsystem' listbrowser is used for AmigaOS bug reports. For other
bug reports, you should select 'Other' in the listbrowser, and type in
the program name in the 'Program' string gadget and the support email
address for the program in the 'EMail to' string gadget.
  Eg. to do a bug report for Report+, you would click 'Other' in the
listbrowser, then type 'Report+' in the 'Program' string gadget, and
'amigansoftware\@gmail.com' in the 'Email to' string gadget.

For MorphOS users:
  You will only be able to access the first tab ("page"), not the second
one where you actually write the bug report. This is because MorphOS has
incompatibilities with texteditor.gadget. It is suggested that you use an
external text editor to write this part of the bug report.

(Taken from official Report documentation, and from 3.0 NDK)

Summary:
    Please make sure the initial one-line bug description you provide
    in each of your reports is as explicit as possible. Engineering's bug
    summary reports and bug processing tools often list only the one-line
    description for each bug. "Bug in Intuition" is a useless title
    for an Intuition subsystem bug. "Pixel trash when window dragged left"
    is a much better title.
Debug tools and wedges:                     eg. Enforcer,MungWall
    Comma-separated names of debug tools and wedges you were using
Company Name: Without Inc., Corp., etc.     eg. Amigan Software
Phone: (AreaCode) Phone-Number              eg. (12) 345-6789
EMail: Your best electronic mail address.
    If UUCP, enter address                  eg. jsmith\@vendor.com
    If other, enter address (SYSTEM)        eg. jsmith (BIX)
    RETURN if none

All bug reports, compatibility problem reports, and enhancement
requests must be generated with the latest Amiga "Report" program,
or must be compatible with the output of the Amiga Report program.
This makes automatic submission and routing of bug reports possible.

Please do not fill in any restricted value fields by hand editing! Only
the Report and Report+ programs can validate these fields.

Mail bug reports to your support manager unless your support manager says
to mail directly to Haage & Partner/Hyperion.
@endnode

@node 2 "Aminet Readme Editor"

The `Uploader' field is, by default, taken from the S:Report.sender
file, if it exists.
  You can use Ctrl-Up and Ctrl-Down to scroll to the extremes of the
`Directory' listview.
  The Architecture field deserves explanation. It is used as follows: For
each architecture for which there is an included binary, you tick the
checkbox to the left of the architecture name. If you want to indicate a
specific architecture version number, you also tick the checkbox to the
right of the architecture name, which will unghost the relevant gadgets
and let you specify a three-part version number (1.2.3 format) and an
operator (<=, <, =, > or >=). If you haven't ticked any architectures, the
architecture will be listed as "any" (ie. no binaries in package).
  Of course you must only open validly formatted readmes unless you want a
visit from the guru :-)

For MorphOS users:
  The "Long description" gadget will not exist when you run the program
under MorphOS. This is because MorphOS has incompatibilities with
texteditor.gadget. It is suggested that you use an external text editor to
write this part of the readme.

(Taken mostly from official Aminet submission documentation)

Output pathname:     eg. RAM:ReportPlus.readme
Don't use version numbers in filenames if possible.
    If you want to make sure your file is not renamed on the CD, only use
letters, digits and _ in the name and make sure the first 8 characters
are unique.
    The maximum file name length is 18 characters including the archiver
suffix (.lha, .lzh). Mixed case is OK, but it should be mainly lowercase.
If your file name is generic (ls, pipe), append your initials (pipe-JU).
    Please do not upload in any other file format than .lha or .lzh, except
that .jpg and .mpg files can be uploaded without putting them in archives.

Short:
A mandatory field. It will be seen in INDEX and RECENT so everyone
can easily learn about your upload. Don't repeat the file name here, but
if several versions of your archive exist, specify the version number
here. Try to explain what the program @{i}does@{ui}. Music should specify the
style and author. Don't boast or use much uppercase.
    If your upload requires a language other than English, please mention
that language here.
    Version numbers are better here than in the filename.

Uploader:            eg. umueller\@amiga.icu.net.ch (Urban Mueller)
It lets you indicate your email address so we can contact you if something
goes wrong (and this happens more often than you think). Please note that
this field is now strictly required - not specifying an email address may
result in your upload getting deleted. The uploader's email address gets
obfuscated now, both in the web interface and in the actual readme. [This
obfuscation is done by Aminet rather than by Report+.]

Author:              eg. amigansoftware\@gmail.com (James Jacobs)
You can indicate who created the piece of software you uploaded.

Type:                eg. games/misc
You can propose a directory [and subdirectory] where the file should be
moved to. Check the file TREE for possible subdirs. If you want a new dir,
read info/start/newdir.txt

Replaces:            eg. biz/patch/PageStreamPatch*
Lets you specify files that are superseded by your upload. Give full path.
Not needed if you overwrite an earlier file with same name.
    You can overwrite old versions of your uploads by uploading again
using the same file name. This is the preferred way to do updates. However
don't update within 10 days of the previous upload.

Requires:            eg. util/misc/ReportPlus.lha, OS2.04+, 4Mb RAM, AGA
Other archives that your upload needs to work, with full path. Also name
OS, mem and chipset requirements here.

Version:             eg. 3.42b
The version number of your upload. Don't use version numbers in filenames
if possible.

Distribution:        eg. NoCD, Aminet
Lets you specify where your upload is OK to distribute.
    If you specify `NoCD', your upload will not appear on the CDs made of
this site.
    If you specify `Aminet', you only give Aminet the distribution
permission.

Architecture:
A mandatory field (henceforth). This field is for notifying which
architecture the package is made for. That is, if the package contains a
binary compiled for a specific architecture you add it here.
    NB! If the application happens to work on another architecture, you
@{i}don't@{ui} add that architecture.
    In addition a version string together with a modifier can be added
for each architecture.
    If a package contains binaries for several architectures you can add
several separated by a semi-colon. Although we encourage you to provide
separate packages for different architectures to improve user experience.
Version number must consist of three @{i}numbers@{ui} (not digits) separated with
dots.

Format:    ARCH1 [MODIFIER VERSION] [; ARCH2 [MODIFIER VERSION]] ...

Archs:     m68k-amigaos
           ppc-amigaos
           ppc-morphos
           ppc-powerup
           ppc-warpup
           x86-aros
           x86-amithlon
           generic

Modifiers: >=, >, =, <, <=

Version:   123.456.789

Example:   Package does not contain binaries compiled for a specific architecture:
               Architecture: all

           Package contains binaries for MorphOS 1.4.2 and newer:
               Architecture: ppc-morphos >= 1.4.2

           Package contains binaries for AmigaOS 3.x and 4.x:
               Architecture: m68k-amigaos >= 3.0.0; ppc-amigaos >= 4.0.0

           Package contains binaries for AmigaOS 3.9.2 and boing bag 2:
               Architecture: m68k-amigaos = 3.9.2

           Package contains binaries for AmigaOS 3.x and PUP and WUP:
               Architecture: m68k-amigaos >= 3.0.0; ppc-warpup; ppc-powerup

           Package contains binaries for AROS and Amithlon:
               Architecture: x86-amithlon; x86-aros

Description:
After a blank line, you may add a longer description, that could for
example be the README found inside the archive. Don't rely on people
downloading the .readme file; the information found there should be in the
archive, as well.
    If your upload is shareware, restricted or just a demo version,
mention that here.
@endnode

@node 3 "Battery-backed RAM Editor"

This allows you to view and alter the contents of the battery-backed
memory, as found in the A3000 and A4000. On other models, this does not
exist, and will thus contain zeroes and will not be really writable.
On platforms that lack battmem.resource, such as MorphOS, this tool
will not be accessible at all.

Changes which have been made, but not yet written to the battery-backed
memory, will be shown in white. Bits which have defined meanings have a
black background.

`Revert' will reread the contents of the battery-backed memory.

`Write' will write your changes to the battery-backed memory, and then
automatically reread the battery-backed memory.

Some bits have defined meanings, as described below. These are linked to
the relevant checkbox gadgets; toggling the gadget will toggle the
relevant bit, and vice versa.

You can load and save the battery-backed RAM from and to a 12-byte file,
using the Project menu or the toolbar.

You can set the contents of the battery-backed RAM from the CLI, without
invoking the Report+ GUI. To do this, specify FUNCTION=9 and the RESET
switch. The other available switches are TIMEOUT, LUNS, SYNC_XFER,
SLOW_SYNC and TAG_QUEUES. The available integer argument is HOST_ID,
which can be 0-7. The entire contents of the battery-backed RAM will be
written to, according to the keywords specified and according to
these rules:

The AMIGA_AMNESIA and SHARED_AMNESIA bits, which are inverted, are always
set (1).

The TIMEOUT, LUNS, SLOW_SYNC, SYNC_XFER and TAG_QUEUES bits are set (1) if
the appropriate switch is given, or cleared (0) otherwise.

The HOST_ID bits, which are inverted, are set according to the HOST_ID
integer, or cleared (0) if it is omitted (which is the same as specifying
HOST_ID=7).

All other bits are cleared (0).

This is provided mainly for users with faulty battery-backed RAM, which
may forget its contents; this apparently can occur with certain
expansion hardware. Calling Report+ in this manner from, for example, the
S:User-startup will automatically refresh the contents of the battery-
backed RAM according to your wishes, without the need for user
intervention. If you don't want to see the 'Done.' message, redirect
output to NIL:.

For example:

    1> ReportPlus 3 RESET
    Done.

This will set short timeouts, no LUNs support, a SCSI host ID of 7,
synchronous transfer requests not initiated, fast synchronous transfer
requests, and no tagged queueing. Or to put it another way, this will
clear (0) every bit of the battery-backed RAM, except for the
AMIGA_AMNESIA and SHARED_AMNESIA bits, which are always set (1).

    1> ReportPlus 3 RESET SLOW_SYNC SYNC_XFER TIMEOUT HOST_ID=4 >NIL:

You would give this command if you want long timeouts, no LUNs support,
a SCSI host ID of 4, synchronous transfer requests initiated, slow
synchronous transfer requests, and no tagged queueing. No output will
be generated.

(Taken from RKRM: Devices)

The battery-backed memory (BattMem) preserves a small portion of Amiga
memory while the system is powered off. Some of the information stored in
this memory is used during the system boot sequence.

The system considers BattMem to be a set of bits rather than bytes. This
is done to conserve the limited space available. All bits are reserved,
and applications should not read, or write undefined bits. Writing bits
should be done with extreme caution since the settings will survive
power-down/power-up.

It is not considered safe to edit undefined bits.

(Taken from resources/battmembits#?.h)

AMIGA_AMNESIA ($00):    The battery-backed memory has had a memory loss.
                        This bit is used as a flag that the user should be
                        notified that all battery-backed bit have been
                        reset and that some attention is required. Zero
                        indicates that a memory loss has occured.

SHARED_AMNESIA ($40):   The battery-backedup memory has had a memory loss.
                        This bit is used as a flag that the user should be
                        notified that all battery-backed bit have been
                        reset and that some attention is required. Zero
                        indicates that a memory loss has occured.

SCSI_TIMEOUT ($01):     Adjusts the timeout value for SCSI device
                        selection. A value of 0 will produce short
                        timeouts (128 ms) while a value of 1 produces long
                        timeouts (2 sec). This is used for Seagate drives
                        (and some Maxtors apparently) that don't respond
                        to selection until they are fully spun up and
                        initialised.

SCSI_LUNS ($02):        Determines if the controller attempts to access
                        logical units above 0 at any given SCSI address.
                        This prevents problems with drives that respond to
                        ALL LUN addresses (instead of only 0 like they
                        should). Default value is 0 meaning don't support
                        LUNs.

SCSI_HOST_ID ($41-$43): A 3-bit field (0-7) that is stored in complemented
                        form (this is so that default value of 0 really
                        means 7). It's used to set the A3000 controller's
                        SCSI ID (on reset).

SCSI_SYNC_XFER ($44):   Determines if the driver should initiate synchronous
                        transfer requests or leave it to the drive to send
                        the first request. This supports drives that crash
                        or otherwise get confused when presented with a sync
                        xfer message. Default=0=sync xfer not initiated.

SCSI_SLOW_SYNC ($45):   Determines if the driver should initiate older
                        <=5MB/s requests instead of synchronous transfer
                        requests (>5MB/s). Note that this has no effect
                        if synchronous transfers are not negotiated by
                        either side. Default=0=fast sync xfer used.

SCSI_TAG_QUEUES ($46):  Determines if the driver should use SCSI-2 tagged
                        queuing which allows the drive to accept and reorder
                        multiple read and write requests. Default=0=tagged
                        queuing NOT enabled.

AMIX ($20-$3F):         See AMIX documentation for these bit definitions.
                        (Please contact us if you have such documentation,
                        so that we can incorporate knowledge of these bit
                        definitions into Report+.)
@endnode

@node 4 "Hardware ID Database"

At startup, your expansion hardware is queried and the cards found are
then available to browse through. Cards are browsed one at a time. You can
navigate forwards and backwards through them.

Various extra information is displayed about the cards:

Serial Number: unique serial number for every card (most cards don't make
               use of this, or use it for another purpose).
ConfigDev    : address of the ConfigDev structure associated with this
               card.
Driver       : address of the relevant node of the driver.
Board Address: address where the card was placed.
Board Size   : size of the card in bytes.
Slot Address : which slot number.
Slot Size    : number of slots.
Type:        : "ACA":     Amiga Classic Accelerator (without AutoConfig)
               "CLK":     Clock port
               "PCI":     Peripheral Component Interconnect card
               $<number>: Zorro card

CLK and PCI detection requires boards.library.

Report+ itself knows over 250 manufacturers and approximately 200 products
(the internal database). Additionally, the AmigaOS versions (when running
under AmigaOS) will automatically make use of boards.library, if you have
it installed. boards.library will automatically make use of
openpci.library, if you have it installed.

The `CPU' and `FPU' gadgets show the detected CPU/FPU of your Amiga. Note
that at least some versions of WinUAE do not set the 68060 flag and
therefore a 68060 may be reported as a 68040 if you don't use
http://aminet.net/package/util/sys/Make060.lha .

The `Registered' checkbox indicates whether the relevant manufacturer
number was properly allocated to that manufacturer by Amiga; that is,
whether the manufacturer number is officially registered. There are
certain manufacturers that have both officially registered and unofficial
numbers. For example, ReadySoft have the officially registered number 2100
and also the unofficial number 8448. It's worth noting that several
manufacturers (notably Phase 5 and GVP) have reused the same product
number for different products.

The most current version of the official Hardware Manufacturer ID Registry
is available at
http://wiki.amigaos.net/index.php/Amiga_Hardware_Manufacturer_ID_Registry
@endnode

@node 5 "IFF/RIFF Viewer"

You can load and browse IFF ("Interchange File Format") and RIFF ("Rip-off
of IFF") files. You can display the contents of certain chunks. Click on
the chunk you are interested in. If it is one of the supported chunk
types, relevant information will appear in the `chunk contents' listview.

It is especially useful for examination of the following IFF/RIFF file
types, as it can interpret the contents of most chunks in them:

    * 3DFL        * DEEP        * ILBM        * RMPG
    * 8SVX        * DR2D        * LMPG        * RSND
    * 16SV        * DTYP        * LWOB        * SMPG
    * ACBM        * FAXX        * LWO2        * SMUS
    * AIFC        * FPBM        * MAUD        * SPLT
    * AIFF        * FTXT        * MC4D        * SPRD
    * ANIM        * GMS         * MPAG        * VLAB
    * CHAP        * HEAD        * PAGE        * WAVE
    * CMPG        * ICON        * PREF        * WORD
    * CTLG        * IFZS        * RGFX        * YUVN
    * CTXT        * ILUS

You can also view information about the purpose, contributor, status,
etc. of any FORM type by entering the FORM ID in the `FORM ID' string
gadget.

There are three levels of knowledge Report+ has:

    *   Firstly, it knows the purpose, contributor and status of most IFF/
        RIFF file types. (Over 150 file types are known.)

    *   Secondly, it knows the purpose of most chunks in most IFF/RIFF
        file types. (Over 300 chunks in about 50 file types are known.)

    *   Thirdly, it knows how to interpret the contents of some chunks in
        the IFF/RIFF file types listed above. (About 100 chunks can be
        interpreted.)

Any value which is out of bounds, according to the official specification
of that FORM, will be appended with `!', or replaced with `?', as
appropriate.

If formatted display of the chunk is not possible, or if `Interpret
chunks?' is off, a hexadecimal/ASCII view of the chunk is displayed
instead.

RIFF files (in particular) are expected be valid. Malformed RIFF files may
cause the program to hang or crash.
  Note there are following file formats are supposed to be, or widely
misbelieved to be, valid IFF FORMs (or RIFFs) but are typically, or
always, malformed (eg. bad header, bad padding, etc.):

    * "IFF" SCHD (SimCity 2000 saves), at least those generated by the
      MS-DOS version;

    * encrypted "IFF" ILBMs, as used by Artworx games (eg. Centerfold
      Squares);

    * "IFF" 3DFL (Electric Image objects);

    * "IFF" PGTB (SAS/C tracebacks);

    * "IFF" RB40 (ReBirth);

    * Electronic Arts The Sims 1 & 2 "IFF" files;

    * "IFF" CIMG (Autodesk Maya);

    * SDIF files (see http://cnmat.berkeley.edu/book/export/html/6291);

    * IFF DJVU files (often these have crap prepended to the header; see
      http://www.djvuzone.org/open/doc/DjVuFileStructure.html);

    * Erlang BEAM compiled modules;

    * Sun TAAC aka VFF aka Sun IFF images;

    * "RIFF" CDRA (CorelDraw); and

    * "IFF" PLBM.

It appears these coders don't really understand the IFF/RIFF standards.
You can use eg. the IFFCheck utility to confirm this.
  Other files such as "IFF" DJVU, IFRS, IFZS, etc. are not strictly
compliant as they use mixed-case chunk IDs, but Report+ can still view
those.
  For IFF files, the IFF content does not have to be at the start of the
file. For example, OS3.5-style icon files contain an embedded IFF FORM,
and DjVu files are prepended with crap. Report+ can automagically find the
IFF data, if it begins within the first 64K of the file. This doesn't
apply to RIFFs (they must begin at the start of the file).

The documentation checkbox display gadgets deserve explanation:

@{b}ADCD 2.1:@{ub} This FORM is documented on the Amiga Developer CD 2.1, in
the Extras/IFF/IFF_FORMs directory.

@{b}RKM:@{ub} This FORM is documented in the Amiga ROM Kernel Reference Manual:
Devices (3rd Edition), Appendix A.
  Note that the documentation for the IFF OFNT FORM is contained within
the IFF DR2D FORM specification.

The `FORM Status' checkbox gadgets indicate the current known status of
the relevant format.

@{b}Standard:@{ub} This FORM is one of the original four types specified in the
original EA 85 IFF standard (8SVX, FTXT, ILBM and SMUS).

The most current version of the official IFF FORM and Chunk Registry is
available at http://wiki.amigaos.net/index.php/IFF_FORM_and_Chunk_Registry
@endnode

@node 6 "Icon Processor"

This lets you perform certain operations on an icon or list of icons.
You can change the icon type (project, tool, etc.), and can also select
whether or not to enable various options which reduce the size of the
icon file(s). This is done as a fix-in-place operation; ie. the input
file(s) is/are overwritten with the output file(s). You can convert a
list of files one after the other in one operation.

An example use for this is to convert a list of drawer icons into project
icons. Report+ allows you to automate such procedures.

You can type multiple arguments, separated by spaces. Any pathnames which
themselves contain spaces must be enclosed within quotes ("). You can also
of course multiselect files using the ASL requester. Wildcards are allowed.

It is possible to use this module directly from the CLI, without invoking
the Report+ GUI. This is done by specifying at least one <file> on the
command line. You may specify several files if desired. When operated in
such a manner, Report+ always uses the last chosen settings (ie. the
settings stored in ReportPlus.config, or the default settings if
ReportPlus.config cannot be loaded).

(Taken from V44 icon.library autodocs)

`Optimize colours': A palette-mapped icon image might not use the entire
icon palette. If this checkbox is FALSE, icon.library does not bother
about this, it expects the creator of the icon to choose its palette
efficiently. But just in case, you can tell icon.library to attempt to
identify how many colours are really in use and optimize its image
compressor for them. This may take extra time and is not recommended for
daily use.

`Preserve planar data': If you decide that the palette-mapped icon
imagery is sufficient to represent an icon, you can tell icon.library
not to store the original, planar icon image data with the icon file.
To do this, set this checkbox to FALSE. Instead of the planar icon
images, a single default image will be stored. This can result in space
savings but may not look too pretty.
@endnode

@node 7 "ASCII Converter"

Various platforms have differing ways of encoding supposedly portable
ASCII files. You can convert between the most important formats.

This is done as a fix-in-place operation; ie. the input file is overwritten
with the output file. You can convert a list of files one after the other
in one operation.

You can type multiple arguments, separated by spaces. Any pathnames which
themselves contain spaces must be enclosed within quotes ("). You can also
of course multiselect files using the ASL requester. Wildcards are allowed.

It is possible to use this module directly from the CLI, without invoking
the Report+ GUI. This is done by specifying at least one <file> on the
command line. You may specify several files if desired. When operated in
such a manner, Report+ always uses the last chosen settings (ie. the
settings stored in ReportPlus.config, or the default settings if
ReportPlus.config cannot be loaded).

These are the seven ASCII formatting issues which can be addressed by
Report+:

    * EOL (end-of-line) conversion.
    * EOF (end-of-file) conversion.
    * High ASCII conversion.
    * Detabulation (tab-to-space conversion) and retabulation (space-to-
      tab conversion).
    * Line wrapping/unwrapping.
    * Stripping of trailing whitespace.
    * Limitation of consecutive blank lines.

@{b}EOL conversion@{ub}

You can convert between Amiga/UNIX (LF), IBM-PC/Atari ST (CR+LF) and
Macintosh (CR) formats.

@{b}EOF conversion@{ub}

You can strip Ctrl-Z end-of-file (EOF) markers (where source is IBM-PC) or
append one to the end of the file (where destination is IBM-PC).

@{b}High ASCII conversion@{ub}

You can convert Amiga/Windows (ECMA Latin-1) characters in the range 160-255 to
their MS-DOS equivalents (if source is Amiga and destination is IBM-PC).
Conversely, you can instead convert appropriate MS-DOS characters into
Amiga/Windows (ECMA Latin-1) format (if source is IBM-PC and destination
is Amiga). Characters which are not converted are passed through unchanged.

See the ISO/DIS 6429.2 and ANSI X3.64-1979 for more information about the
ECMA Latin-1 format.

@{b}Detabulation@{ub}

You can convert tabs in the file into their equivalent number of spaces.
The source tab size defaults to 8 but may be changed.

@{b}Line wrapping/unwrapping@{ub}

If a file contains EOLs in the middle of paragraphs, you can unwrap the
words so that such EOLs are converted to spaces. When using this option,
EOLs will only preserved or converted at the end of paragraphs.

You can also do word wrapping. If a file is already word-wrapped, and
you want to re-wrap it to a different column width, you should unwrap it
first. You can have an EOL inserted between each paragraph; this option is
only used when wrapping, not when unwrapping or preserving.

@{b}Stripping of trailing whitespace@{ub}

This removes all spaces and tabs from the ends of each line.

@{b}Limitation of consecutive blank lines@{ub}

This will remove any completely blank lines beyond your specified limit.
Eg. If the file has 5 blank lines between each paragraph and you choose
to limit it to 3 blank lines, the remaining 2 blank lines are removed.
For best results with this, turn on the whitespace stripping, otherwise
lines containing only spaces and/or tabs will not be considered to be
blank.

@{b}ANSI colour code stripping@{ub}

This will remove any ANSI colour codes from the file. Both the short ($9B)
and long ($1B $5B) CSI formats are supported. However, not all ANSI codes
are supported. Some non-colour ANSI codes may cause problems, so you
should not use this on files which contain other kinds of ANSI sequences.
@endnode

@node 8 "Path Size Report"

This is useful for quickly seeing which directories are taking up the most
space. Directory sizes are calculated from the totals of their contents,
including subdirectories. You can specify any path you like, so that you
can specify either an entire drive/partition or any directory within it.

The `Root' and `Parent' directories allow you to easily move through the
directory tree of the current drive.

Directories are marked with the `*' symbol. If you click on one of these
directories which is at the top nesting level, you will go inside it.

If `Include slack?' is ticked, the size of each file is calculated
according to the actual space taken up on the disk, eg. the block size
multiplied by the number of blocks used.

You can view the sizes of the files and directories in bytes, kilobytes,
megabytes, or blocks. If you view in blocks it does not matter whether
`Include slack?' is ticked - slack is of course included. Note that the
sizes shown never include header or extension blocks, only data blocks.
Thus, the true size of any given file or directory will be slightly more
than indicated. Also note data blocks are assumed to contain only data;
this is a true assumption for filing systems such as FFS but not for
filing systems such as OFS.

If you are using Report+ in an emulation environment such as UAE you may
not get accurate results for `Free on volume' and 'Volume capacity'. This
is due to the way UAE reports drive information and is unavoidable: you
will experience the same problems with the Info AmigaDOS command, for
example.

If you enable `Log to file?', then whenever you do a path size report,
the report will be appended to the specified file.

You can decide how deep into the directory tree you would like to show
with the `Nesting Level' gadget, or you can instead decide to show
everything (infinitely deep).

You can also suppress the display of files/directories which have not
been modified since before a given date. This is useful when you just want
to see what has changed since eg. your last backup.

Adjusting the size units, the `Show subdirectories?' settings, the `Show
files?' setting, etc. will automatically trigger an (almost-)immediate
update of the results list.

The maximum number of directories/files that can be handled is limited
only by available memory.

You can also fix protection bits whilst doing the path size report.
If this option is selected, any files found which have any of their RWED
bits clear (to deny access) will have those bits set (to permit access).
The HAPS bits will be preserved.

You can also automatically delete unwanted files. You can delete .fastdir
(created by the CLImate directory utility), _UAEFSDB.___ (created by the
WinUAE emulator), and/or any other wildcard, in the selected path (or
subdirectories thereof).
  Note that there is a bug in WinUAE's UAEFSDB support: Amiga programs
(including Report+) cannot "see" (and therefore cannot delete)
_UAEFSDB.___ files when running inside WinUAE, even if the "disable
UAEFSDB-support" checkbox in the "Hard drives" configuration panel of
WinUAE is ticked. Therefore, for this option to be useful, you need to
use an old version of WinUAE (pre-UAEFSDB support), or a different Amiga
emulator, or a real Amiga.
@endnode

@node 9 "Path Differences Report"

This function is a general-purpose directory comparison tool.
  You can compare two directories immediately, or you can compare a
directory against a contents list ("snapshot") you have generated
earlier.
  It supports comparison of versions, dates, times, sizes and CRC32
checksums.

It will tell you:

    . 2nd-path files found which ARE in the 1st-path AND which have
        correct versions/dates/times/sizes/CRC32s ("same" files) (green);
    ! 2nd-path files found which ARE in the 1st-path BUT which have
        incorrect versions/dates/times/sizes/CRC32s ("changed" files)
        (orange);
    + 2nd-path files found which are NOT in the 1st-path ("added" files)
        (cyan); and
    - 2nd-path files NOT found which ARE in the 1st-path ("missing" files)
        (red).

(You can suppress reporting of any or all of these categories, using the
appropriate `Show' option.)

One use for this is to make a snapshot immediately after installing
AmigaOS (and the Boing Bags). This will give you a snapshot of a
clean AmigaOS installation. Then you can later compare your SYS: partition
against this to determine which files have changed. This can be helpful
in, for example, uninstalling software, or to check whether any system
files have been accidentally deleted, or accidentally overwritten with an
old version, or infected with a linkvirus, etc. It has also proven useful
for uninstalling software. Or you could compare a new release of a package
against an older release to see which files have changed.

The three operations are:

Make snapshot of directory for later:
   This will examine (thoroughly) the 1st directory path, and generate the
   named snapshot file.

Compare directory against snapshot from earlier:
   This will load the named snapshot file, and will then examine the 2nd
   directory path, and compare the two. Ie. the same as 'compare two
   directories now', except that the 1st directory is read from the
   snapshot file instead of from a live directory.

Compare two directories now:
   This will examine the 1st and 2nd directory paths, and compare the two.

You can turn off eg. version checking to speed up the process (except when
making a snapshot). Icons are never version checked.

After the operation is completed, the log file (if any) will be written
and you will see the report in a listbrowser gadget.
  For the compare operations, if 'Log to file?' is selected, the report
will be not only displayed in the listbrowser gadget, but will also be
appended to the given logfile, so that you have a permanent log of the
session for your reference.
  For the 'Make snapshot of directory for later' operation, the
listbrowser items will be shown in white. For the compare operations, the
listbrowser items will be shown in green/orange/cyan/red, according to
category (as explained above). "Expected" refers to the snapshot file or
1st directory. "Found" refers to the 2nd directory.

You can use Ctrl-Up/Down to scroll to the extremes of the listbrowser,
Shift-Up/Down to scroll by pages, and Up/Down to scroll one line.

Here are examples of using this tool. Assuming you want to compare two
directories, called foo and bar:

1. Choose 'Make snapshot of directory for later'.
2. Enter foo in the '1st directory path:' field.
3. Click 'Go'.
   Now the snapshot file (eg. PROGDIR:ReportPlus.snapshot) is created.
   The contents of foo are shown in white in the listbrowser.
4. Choose 'Compare directory against snapshot from earlier'.
5. Click 'Options' and set the options you want.
6. Enter bar in the 'Path:' field.
7. Click 'Go'.
   Now bar is compared against the contents of the snapshot file, and the
   results are displayed in the listbrowser. (A logfile is also generated,
   if you chose to generate one.)

Or, easier:

1. Choose 'Compare two directories now'.
2. Enter foo in the '1st directory path:' field.
3. Enter bar in the '2nd directory path:' field.
4. Click 'Options' and set the options you want.
5. Click 'Go'.
   Now bar is compared against foo, and the results are displayed in the
   listbrowser. (A logfile is also generated, if you chose to generate
   one.)
@endnode

@node Cred "Credits and Licence"

@{b}Credits@{ub}

Report+ was designed and programmed by James Jacobs of Amigan Software.
Graphics were drawn by Martin `Mason' Merz. FindMOS (used by the
installer) was written by Christian Rosentreter.

Special thanks to Thomas Beck, Jean-Marie Boucher, Craig Daines, Emiliano
Esposito, Costel Mincea, and Ernest Unrau for their suggestions and bug
reports, and to Jeff aka Xenic for bug fixes.

@{b}EMail:@{ub}                  amigansoftware\@gmail.com

@{b}Amiga Developer Number:@{ub} AD874

@{b}Website:@{ub}                http://amigan.1emu.net/releases/

@{b}Licence@{ub}

Report+ is open source freeware. These are the licence conditions:

    * you are not allowed to sell it, or modified versions of it, without
      consent;

    * any modified versions must be clearly marked as such, and not be
      misrepresented as being the original software;

    * you are not allowed to claim you wrote this software, or to remove
      or alter the existing credits (though you may append to them as
      appropriate);

    * you may distribute this unmodified executable either with or without
      the source code, at your discretion. (The official release packages
      will always include source code.) However, modified versions
      (including ports) must include both the executable and source code;

    * software into which code or algorithms are copied must be open
      source, and appropriate credit must be given;

    * you must allow us the right to backport improvements you make to
      this software or algorithms;

    * you are not allowed to modify the software to deliberately insert
      logic bombs, spyware, digital restrictions management, copy
      protection, online activation, virii or other malware;

    * any package or compilation of which this software forms a part must
      be entirely free of logic bombs, spyware, digital restrictions
      management, copy protection, online activation and other malware;
      and

    * there is no warranty on this software.

We seek to provide the most rights and freedoms possible to users,
modifiers and distributors of this software. We believe that the above
licence meets these needs.

If you would like to become an official co-developer of this utility,
please contact us.

@{b}Bugs@{ub}

Amiga development and style guidelines have been adhered to, using the
official Amiga Technical Reference Series as authoritive reference.

This bug has been reported, although we cannot reproduce it: emailing of
bug reports apparently fails on some Amigas ("Socket connection failed!").

Please contact us immediately if any bugs are found. Please use the
supplied @{"bug reporting tool" link 1} :-) if possible; it is the easiest
method. Do not assume that the bug has already been reported by another
user; this is most unlikely.

@{b}Future@{ub}

It is our intention to update Report+ as necessary so that it always
matches the latest official revisions of the relevant file formats, etc.
and of course to immediately fix any bugs found.

Contact us to suggest new features.

@{b}Source code@{ub}

SAS/C and StormC source code is provided. The source code of V6.16 was
linted weakly with LCLint.

The release binary was compiled under StormC 4.0. However, should also be
to compile it under SAS/C 6.58 (this has not been done recently), the main
differences being that the Storm version is about 20K larger, does not
support tool types, and cannot be exited cleanly whilst another instance
of itself is running, whereas the SAS/C version lacks 64-bit (>4Gb)
support.

The HunkShort utility (http://aminet.net/dev/misc/HunkShort.lha) is used
on the generated executable to reduce its size.
@endnode

@node Rele "Other Releases"

@{b}Worm Wars@{ub} (Windows, AmigaOS 2-3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS, AROS, GBA)

Worm Wars is an advanced Tron/Snake-style arcade game for up to 4
simultaneous players.

There are 36 types of creature, 36 types of object, and 9 types of bonus
level. The integral level editor allows you to load, edit and save user
levelsets. There is support for playing MED and IFF 8SVX files as music
and sound effects respectively.

It is can be played by one player, or as a competitive multiplayer
game, and demo mode is available. Amiga or human control can be specified
for any worm. Two keyboard players, four joystick players, and/or four
CD32 gamepad players are supported. It is system-friendly, style
compliant and screenmode-sensitive.

The supported languages are currently English, German, Greek, Italian and
Spanish.

@{b}Saga@{ub} (AmigaOS 3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS, AROS)

This is a conversion of the 1981 TSR boardgame "Saga: Age of Heroes", for
up to 6 players. Players can be controlled by human or Amiga.
  In Saga: Age of Heroes, players defeat evil monsters, win fabulous
treasures and rule great kingdoms in their quest to gain glory and be the
one hero whose memory will live on forever in the songs and stories of the
age.
  It is currently available in English, German and Italian. SAS/C and
StormC source code is included.

@{b}AmiArcadia/WinArcadia@{ub} (AmigaOS 3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS, Windows)

AmiArcadia and WinArcadia are multi-emulators of these machines:

    * the Emerson Arcadia 2001 console family (Bandai, Emerson,
      Grandstand, Intervision, Leisure-Vision, Leonardo, MPT-03, Ormatu,
      Palladium, Poppy, Robdajet, Tele-Fever, Tempest, Tryom, Tunix,
      etc.) (1982);
    * the Interton VC 4000 console family (Acetronic, Fountain, Hanimex,
      Interton, Prinztronic, Radofin, Rowtron, Voltmace, Waddington, etc.)
      (c. 1978);
    * the Elektor TV Games Computer (1979);
    * PIPBUG-based machines (EA 77up2, EA 78up5, Signetics Adaptable Board
      Computer, Eurocard 2650, etc.) (c. 1977-1978);
    * the Signetics Instructor 50 trainer (1978);
    * the Central Data 2650 computer (1977);
    * the Astro Wars, Cat and Mouse, Galaxia, and Laser Battle coin-ops by
      Zaccaria (1979-1982);
    * the Malzak 1 and 2 coin-ops by Kitronix (c. 1980);
    * the Chaos 2 computer (1983);
    * the Dolphin trainer (1977);
    * the PHUNSY computer (c. 1980);
    * AY-3-8550/8600-based Pong systems (c. 1976-1977);
    * the Ravensburger Selbstbaucomputer aka 2650 Minimal Computer trainer
      (1984); and
    * the MIKIT 2650 trainer (1978).

Features include: ReAction GUI, load/save snapshots, windowed and full-
screen modes, CPU tracing, trainer, drag and drop support, graphics
scaling, automatic load/save of configuration/game, keyboard/joystick/
gamepad/paddle/mouse/trackball support, autofire, turbo mode, gameplay
recording/playback, PAL/NTSC modes, sprite demultiplexing, help windows,
source code, debugger, frame skipping, redefinable keys, save screenshots
(4 supported formats), ARexx port, network play, real-time monitor, locale
support, game selection sidebar, text-to-speech, printer output,
undithering, support for ZIPped games, clipboard support, palette editor,
tone retuning, high score management, force feedback, sprite editor, 3D,
assembler, CALM support.

The supported languages are currently English, Dutch, French, German,
Greek, Italian, Russian and Spanish.

@{b}Super Bug Advance@{ub} (GBA)

This is a port of a subset of the Ami/WinArcadia 11.71 emulator to the
Nintendo Game Boy Advance platform, for the purpose of emulating the
Super Bug and Capture games.

@{b}Africa@{ub} (AmigaOS 3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS)

This is a conversion of the 1977 3W boardgame "Africa", for up to 5
players. Players can be controlled by human or Amiga. SAS/C and StormC
source code is included.

In this game each player takes the role of one of the powers attempting to
establish or maintain a sphere of influence in the southern half of the
African continent. By interfering in the economic stability and political
alliance of nations, and by subsidising them, the players attempt to
extend their political control of Africa, while diminishing the control
of their opponents.

There is the opportunity to set up governments in favour of the players,
encourage revolutions, start wars between the African nations and even
introduce armies of the player-powers into the continent.

@{b}Koules@{ub} (Windows, AmigaOS 3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS, AROS)

These are the Amiga and Windows port of Koules 1.4, a popular arcade game
for Linux and OS/2.

Features: 1-5 players simultaneously, sound effects, triple keyboard and
quadruple joystick support, source code, turbo speed on/off, autofire on/
off.

@{b}CodeWar@{ub} (Windows, AmigaOS 3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS)

These are ports (from Linux) of the CodeWar simulator, a game for
programmers.

CodeWar is essentially a simulation engine which allows multiple processes
to execute simultaneously within the same virtual environment. This
in turn provides programmers with the facilities to compete against one
another by seeing who can write the program which exists the longest
within this environment. Unlike other simulators such as CRobots, the
competing robots are real native programs and may thus be written in any
language.

Less formally, CodeWar allows programmers to create programs (robots)
which can compete against one another using a variety of
armaments (cannons, missiles, etc.) by executing them at the same time
within the CodeWar simulator. Robots have the ability to detect these
other robots and make up their own strategies to outsmart other
programmers' code.

@{b}Multi-game Character Editor@{ub} (AmigaOS 3, AmigaOS 4, MorphOS)

MCE (Multi-game Character Editor) allows editing of character files, saved
games and high score tables for these 52 games:

    * Bard's Tale 1-3 & Construction Set (1987-1992)
    * BattleTech (1989)
    * Bloodwych (1989)
    * Chambers of Shaolin (1989)
    * Champions of Krynn (1990)
    * Citadel of Vras (1989)
    * Dark Castle (1988)
    * Deja Vu 1 & 2 (1986-1989)
    * Demon's Winter (1989)
    * Dragon Wars (1990)
    * Druid 2 (1988)
    * Eye of the Beholder 1 & 2 (1990-1992)
    * Faery Tale Adventure (1986)
    * Grand Monster Slam (1989)
    * Great Giana Sisters/Hard 'n' Heavy (1988-1989)
    * Heroes of the Lance (1988)
    * Hillsfar (1989)
    * Impossible Mission 2 (1988)
    * Keef the Thief (1989)
    * Legend of Faerghail (1990)
    * Legend of Lothian (1991)
    * Might & Magic 2 (1990)
    * Neuromancer (1989)
    * Nitro (1990)
    * Phantasie 1 & 3 (1987)
    * Pirates! (1990)
    * Pool of Radiance (1990)
    * Questron 2 (1988)
    * Return of the Jedi (1988)
    * Rogue (1986)
    * Shadowgate (1987)
    * Shadowlands (1992)
    * Sinbad and the Throne of the Falcon (1987)
    * Temple of Apshai (1986)
    * Times of Lore (1988)
    * Transylvania 1 & 2 (1986)
    * Ultima 3-6 (1986-1992)
    * Winter Games (1987)
    * Wizardry 6 (1990)
    * World Games (1987)
    * Zerg (1989)

@{b}Tunnels & Trolls@{ub} (Windows, AmigaOS 2)

This is an implementation of the Tunnels & Trolls game (5th Edition), in
its solitaire form, consisting of the game engine and 24 adventures. It
allows you to play the adventures without pen, paper, dice, cards, nor the
adventures themselves. The complete T&T rulebook will prove handy but is
not essential.
  The included adventures are:

    * Abyss
    * Amulet of the Salkti
    * Arena of Khazan
    * Beyond the Silvered Pane
    * Blue Frog Tavern
    * Buffalo Castle
    * Captif d'Yvoire
    * Caravan to Tiern
    * City of Terrors
    * Dargon's Dungeon
    * Deathtrap Equalizer
    * Gamesmen of Kasar
    * Goblin Lake
    * Labyrinth
    * Mistywood
    * Naked Doom
    * Overkill
    * Red Circle
    * Sewers of Oblivion
    * Sorcerer Solitaire
    * Sword for Hire
    * Trollstone Caverns
    * Weirdworld

@{b}Microdot@{ub} (Windows)

This is a conversion of the 1975 PB board game "Microdot", for up to 4
players. Players can be controlled by human or IBM PC. Visual C 6.0
source code is included.

The object of Microdot is to capture a Diplomatic Bag from any enemy
territory to your own and bring it back safely to your own HQ square.
The first player to succeed in this mission wins the game.
@endnode

